  "opinion": "As a woman who grew up in Milan with a father who was a PhD holder and a mother who had only primary school education, I’ve seen firsthand how science and education can be both a bridge and a barrier. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the quiet moments when a young girl hesitates to ask a question in class because she fears being labeled 'not smart enough.' It’s also about the way textbooks often highlight male scientists without acknowledging the women who laid the groundwork. When I was teaching in my youth, I noticed how many students, especially girls, would disengage from physics and engineering because they didn’t see themselves reflected in the stories we told. This gap isn’t accidental; it’s shaped by subtle biases in our schools and workplaces. We should address it, but not with top-down mandates that ignore the lived experiences of those who’ve been marginalized. Instead, we need to create spaces where girls feel safe to explore science without judgment. My own journey—starting with simple experiments in my kitchen and later pursuing a passion for understanding the world through the lens of physics—teaches me that encouragement matters more than labels. We must celebrate the women who have contributed to science but are often forgotten, and we must ensure that future generations see themselves in the stories we tell. After all, science belongs to everyone who is curious, not just those who fit a narrow definition of 'suitable.'",
